He was awful in abusive and the guy is a kind
of Aspergersy mathematician.

00:38:08.080 --> 00:38:15.130
And his nemesis is a physicist that he went
to university with.

00:38:15.130 --> 00:38:18.030
And there's all, it's just, it's diabolical.

00:38:18.030 --> 00:38:21.589
And it's got a plot twist I did not see coming.

00:38:21.589 --> 00:38:23.950
It's got a great plot twist.

00:38:23.950 --> 00:38:27.420
So I've also got my stack of books you know
that I want to read.

00:38:27.420 --> 00:38:28.420
I want to read Gilead.

00:38:28.420 --> 00:38:34.100
I got a lot of books, all kinds of books that
I just don't get to.

00:38:34.100 --> 00:38:35.100
Yes.

00:38:35.100 --> 00:38:45.300
&gt;&gt;Male #4: The description you have of you
know how people's lives are so networked and

00:38:45.300 --> 00:38:50.940
you know we're so vulnerable with all this
information.

00:38:50.940 --> 00:38:54.683
It reminded me of "The Net" you know the Sandra
Bullock movie.

00:38:54.683 --> 00:38:55.683
&gt;&gt;Hallie: Yeah.

00:38:55.683 --> 00:38:56.683
&gt;&gt;Male #4: I was wondering where that fits
in and now it's been what, 17 years since

00:38:56.683 --> 00:38:57.683
it came out?

00:38:57.683 --> 00:38:58.683
&gt;&gt;Hallie: That's true.

00:38:58.683 --> 00:38:59.683
I had forgotten about that movie.

00:38:59.683 --> 00:39:00.683
Yeah.

00:39:00.683 --> 00:39:01.683
&gt;&gt;Male #4: [Inaudible] things may have changed
or how we've accepted things that.

00:39:01.683 --> 00:39:03.630
&gt;&gt;Hallie: I think we've accepted a lot of
things.

00:39:03.630 --> 00:39:09.330
One of the things that is key in this book
is a flash mob.

00:39:09.330 --> 00:39:15.320
And of course, when the net was written, flash
mobs hadn't yet been invented.

00:39:15.320 --> 00:39:21.190
But I think there's a playfulness about the
Internet that was not.

00:39:21.190 --> 00:39:22.839
Because it's just a part of your life.

00:39:22.839 --> 00:39:24.599
I mean it's just there.

00:39:24.599 --> 00:39:27.800
I think it was much newer then.

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:31.320
And I think, but I love the playfulness of
it.

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:36.710
I love Facebook, I love being able to connect
to people I don't know.

00:39:36.710 --> 00:39:40.339
I like trying to assess out which people are,
are not real.

00:39:40.339 --> 00:39:41.339
[Laughs]

00:39:41.339 --> 00:39:48.560
I don't know, I guess, I think it's possible
to take it a lot less seriously than.

00:39:48.560 --> 00:39:50.230
But I do love those.

00:39:50.230 --> 00:39:53.690
Has anybody seen the new "Sherlock Holmes"?

00:39:53.690 --> 00:39:54.890
Yeah.

00:39:54.890 --> 00:40:01.670
On public television, there's a new "Sherlock
Holmes" with Cumberbatch, great name.

00:40:01.670 --> 00:40:03.310
It's the name of the.

00:40:03.310 --> 00:40:09.010
But what's cool about it is it's set in the
present and it's full of computery things.

00:40:09.010 --> 00:40:14.450
You know they're like little butterflies that
pop up every once in a while.

00:40:14.450 --> 00:40:25.210
And it's extremely cool that, and weird because
I always think of Sherlock Holmes as the perfect

00:40:25.210 --> 00:40:29.990
vehicle for steam punk.

00:40:29.990 --> 00:40:35.100
Which in its way is sort of a twisted version,
cause it's set in the old-time me.

00:40:35.100 --> 00:40:40.030
But this is taking the same idea but setting
it absolutely in modern day.

00:40:40.030 --> 00:40:42.250
I think it's very cool.

00:40:42.250 --> 00:40:43.670
Anyway, I think it's become more playful.

00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:45.640
I think were less afraid.

00:40:45.640 --> 00:40:49.450
I think we know, I think we've just stop worrying.

00:40:49.450 --> 00:40:50.990
Because how can you do otherwise?

00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:52.750
I mean, you know.

00:40:52.750 --> 00:40:55.829
I mean you don't get those e-mails every other
day.

00:40:55.829 --> 00:40:58.599
Oh my God, there's a virus.

00:40:58.599 --> 00:41:02.410
And, all that stuff has really settled down.

00:41:02.410 --> 00:41:06.420
And I think people have gotten smarter about
protecting, I hope, our computers.

00:41:06.420 --> 00:41:08.710
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Overloaded and turned it off.

00:41:08.710 --> 00:41:10.950
&gt;&gt;Hallie: Yeah I think, I think you're right.

00:41:10.950 --> 00:41:12.349
I think you're right.

00:41:12.349 --> 00:41:13.349
Yes.

00:41:13.349 --> 00:41:20.710
&gt;&gt;Male #5: So you wrote a book on how to write
a mystery novel.

00:41:20.710 --> 00:41:21.710
&gt;&gt;Hallie: I did yeah.

00:41:21.710 --> 00:41:22.710
&gt;&gt;Male #5: And you decided that wasn't right
thing to do?

00:41:22.710 --> 00:41:23.710
&gt;&gt;Hallie: Oh no no.

00:41:23.710 --> 00:41:24.800
It's just that that process that I talked
about in that book didn't work for the book

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:25.800
I was writing.

00:41:25.800 --> 00:41:28.100
&gt;&gt;Male #5: So are you going to rewrite the
book?

00:41:28.100 --> 00:41:30.400
&gt;&gt;Hallie: No, because it's chaos.

00:41:30.400 --> 00:41:33.780
You cannot recommend chaos to people.

00:41:33.780 --> 00:41:35.020
[laughter]

00:41:35.020 --> 00:41:43.250
I mean, what I say in "Writing and Selling
Your Mystery Novel" is that writing a novel

00:41:43.250 --> 00:41:45.170
is a very personal process.

00:41:45.170 --> 00:41:48.730
Everyone will do it differently because we're,
you have to take advantage of your strengths

00:41:48.730 --> 00:41:50.790
and we all have different strengths.

00:41:50.790 --> 00:41:55.790
And so, on the other hand, it doesn't hurt
to hear how other people do it and try some

00:41:55.790 --> 00:41:59.230
of those techniques that they have and see
if they work for you.

00:41:59.230 --> 00:42:02.031
So I kinda hedged my bets when I wrote it.

00:42:02.031 --> 00:42:03.490
And I still believe that.

00:42:03.490 --> 00:42:09.690
And I also think that different books write
differently.

00:42:09.690 --> 00:42:14.220
This book for instance, "There Was an Old
Woman," I knew the ending.

00:42:14.220 --> 00:42:15.910
It's the first thing I knew.

00:42:15.910 --> 00:42:19.500
I absolutely knew the ending, never gonna
change.

00:42:19.500 --> 00:42:21.450
That's the ending.

00:42:21.450 --> 00:42:26.790
There's a huge plot twist at the end and I
had it from the beginning.

00:42:26.790 --> 00:42:35.970
In "Come and Find Me" there's a final scene
where she confronts the person who's been

00:42:35.970 --> 00:42:39.700
jerking her around.

00:42:39.700 --> 00:42:47.410
And I knew she was going to one up him.

00:42:47.410 --> 00:42:53.060
She was gonna, she was gonna get him.

00:42:53.060 --> 00:42:55.030
But I didn't know how.

00:42:55.030 --> 00:42:59.130
And so, I mean I just, I was afraid of writing
up to that point cause I was gonna have figure

00:42:59.130 --> 00:43:00.130
it out.

00:43:00.130 --> 00:43:01.140
And I did.

00:43:01.140 --> 00:43:03.820
So it's just, it's very different everybody
right.

00:43:03.820 --> 00:43:07.940
But I do think, I mean I remember when I was
first starting, the first writing conference

00:43:07.940 --> 00:43:08.940
I ever went to.

00:43:08.940 --> 00:43:12.410
And they're great to go to if you're a writer
cause you hear all kinds, you hear every writer

00:43:12.410 --> 00:43:14.160
tell their process and it's so different.

00:43:14.160 --> 00:43:17.130
So you just give up of there being one way.

00:43:17.130 --> 00:43:21.700
But I remember there was the keynote speaker
was some very well published writer.

00:43:21.700 --> 00:43:23.609
You know Pulitzer Prize winner, blah blah
blah.

00:43:23.609 --> 00:43:29.869
And she said, somebody asked her, "What's
your writing process?"

00:43:29.869 --> 00:43:34.430
And she said, in all seriousness, "It's magic."

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:42.060
And you know, I thought that's like saying
"I can do it and you can't."

00:43:42.060 --> 00:43:43.060
You know?

00:43:43.060 --> 00:43:46.410
It's the ultimate auteur.

00:43:46.410 --> 00:43:48.951
And it really turned me off, that was before
I wrote my book.

00:43:48.951 --> 00:43:50.770
I thought that's bullshit.

00:43:50.770 --> 00:43:52.630
There's a million ways to write a book.

00:43:52.630 --> 00:43:55.140
So tell us what yours is and we'll find out
what some.

00:43:55.140 --> 00:43:58.090
And then you put it together for yourself.

00:43:58.090 --> 00:44:00.460
It's just a process to an end.

00:44:00.460 --> 00:44:01.460
Yes.

00:44:01.460 --> 00:44:02.869
&gt;&gt;Male #6: It sounds little bit like Nash,
you know John Nash when he went crazy right?

00:44:02.869 --> 00:44:12.080
It's like how come you didn't know that becoming
the Emperor of Antarctica was weird.

00:44:12.080 --> 00:44:19.280
He said, "Well it came to me the same way
the mathematical ideas came to me."

00:44:19.280 --> 00:44:20.320
&gt;&gt;Hallie: Yeah, yeah.

00:44:20.320 --> 00:44:22.390
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Sorta the same way.

00:44:22.390 --> 00:44:27.680
&gt;&gt;Hallie: Well see that's the problem with,
the kind of books that I write really do have

00:44:27.680 --> 00:44:31.160
a form.

00:44:31.160 --> 00:44:35.740
And that's one of the things that I write
about in that writing book is what is, what

00:44:35.740 --> 00:44:41.660
do people expect when they pick up a book
that's been shelved with the mystery books.

00:44:41.660 --> 00:44:44.480
You know, there's a certain expectation.

00:44:44.480 --> 00:44:50.040
And that's not to say you have to write a
book that conforms to those expectations but

00:44:50.040 --> 00:44:54.589
readers will not be happy if they pulled it
off the mystery shelf and it doesn't feel

00:44:54.589 --> 00:44:55.660
like a mystery.

00:44:55.660 --> 00:44:59.550
So what I was writing about a lot was the
structure of a mystery.

00:44:59.550 --> 00:45:05.950
It always always opens with a scene that throws
a character off-balance.

00:45:05.950 --> 00:45:08.590
Just like a movie actually.

00:45:08.590 --> 00:45:11.260
Movies always open with those, start noticing.

00:45:11.260 --> 00:45:16.109
I mean they always open with, it doesn't have
to be a dead body, it can be a guy parking

00:45:16.109 --> 00:45:22.040
his Porsche at the apartment building, coming
up the stairs walking down the hall.

00:45:22.040 --> 00:45:24.020
The door to his apartment is ajar.

00:45:24.020 --> 00:45:27.170
He pushes it open all the furniture is gone.

00:45:27.170 --> 00:45:31.150
And there's a red stiletto heel in the middle
of the bare floor.

00:45:31.150 --> 00:45:32.150
That's a great opening.

00:45:32.150 --> 00:45:33.790
I mean I haven't written that one yet.

00:45:33.790 --> 00:45:34.790
[laughter]

00:45:34.790 --> 00:45:35.790
But I will one day.

00:45:35.790 --> 00:45:37.450
That's a short story.

00:45:37.450 --> 00:45:40.560
So you know, it's a what's going on here moment.

00:45:40.560 --> 00:45:43.770
And that's how you always want to always start
